{"title_page": "Guinea/Transportation", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Transport in Guinea]]\n\n{{R from subpage}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Transport in Guinea]]\n", "name_user": "1234qwer1234qwer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:R from subpage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Guinea/Transportation&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Guinea/Communications", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[Telecommunications in Guinea]]\n\n{{R from subpage}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[Telecommunications in Guinea]]\n", "name_user": "1234qwer1234qwer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:R from subpage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Guinea/Communications&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu\n| image = \n| caption =\n| spouse = [[Kaiko\u02bbokalani]]<br />[[Kuakini]]<br />[[Keaweamahi Kinimaka]]\n| issue = [[Kamanele]]\n| father = \n| mother = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{circa|1843}}\n| death_place = [[Honolulu]], [[Oahu]]\n| burial_place = \n}}\n\n'''Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu''' or '''Kaniu\u02bbopioha\u02bbaheo''' (died {{circa|1843}}) was a high chiefess ([[ali\u02bbi]]) and member of the royal family of the [[Hawaiian Kingdom]]. She was also known as '''Lydia Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu'''.\n\n==Genealogy and family==\nHa\u02bbaheo Kaniu was born in the late 18th-century. Sources on Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu's genealogy are conflicting. An 1858 court case named Kalailua as the mother of Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu and stated Kalailua was sister of [[\u02bbAikanaka (father of Keohok\u0101lole)|\u02bbAikanaka]] (maternal grandfather of her future ''h\u0101nai'' son [[Kal\u0101kaua]]).<ref name=\"Court1866\" /> An 1874 account in the [[Hawaiian language]] newspaper ''Ka Nuhou Hawaii'' listed her parent as Kalailua and Keaweaimoku and further specified that Kalailua was the child of Kaoo and Kamakaeheikuli.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ka Papa Alii O Hawaii I Hoonohonoho Pono Ia|date=January 7, 1874|newspaper=Ka Nuhou Hawaii|volume=1|issue=10|page=3|url=http://nupepa.org/gsdl2.5/cgi-bin/nupepa?e=d-0nupepa--00-0-0--010---4-----mid---0-1l--1en-Zz-1---20-about---0003-1-0000utfZz-8-00&a=d&cl=CL2.30&d=HASH04cfa1db90bd9eb14e1b7d.3|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHistorian [[Abraham Fornander]] named High Chiefess \u02bbAkahi as her mother, who was a sister of [[Keawemauhili]], Ali\u02bbi Nui of [[Hilo, Hawaii|Hilo]] and a rival of King [[Kamehameha I]] who conquered the Hawaiian Islands into a unified kingdom by 1810. This \u02bbAkahi was the foster mother of Keawemauhili's orphan daughter [[Kapi\u02bbolani (chiefess)|Kapi\u02bbolani]] who became a later famous convert to [[Christianity]].{{sfn|Fornander|1880|page=320}} According to historian Sammy Amalu, she was the daughter of \u02bbAkahi-a-Kawalu (different from Fornander's \u02bbAkahi) and [[Ke\u014dua|Ke\u014dua Kalanikupuapa\u02bb\u012bkalaninui Ahilapalapa]], the father of Kamehameha I.{{sfn|Pratt|1920|pages=40\u201342}}<ref name=\"Keoua\">{{Hawaiian Dictionaries|Sacred Prince Keoua Had Six Official Wives|dic=royal|id=D0.4.99|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> \n\nHa\u02bbaheo Kaniu married to [[Kaiko\u02bbokalani]], the son of Kamehameha I and [[Peleuli]].{{sfn|Fornander|1880|page=320}}{{sfn|Kamakau|1992|page=250}} She also married [[Kuakini]], who adopted the name John Adams and served as [[Governors of Hawaii (island)|Governor of Hawaii Island]]. Kuakini was also the younger brother of Kamehameha I's favorite wife [[Ka\u02bbahumanu]] who served as ''[[Kuhina Nui]]'' (regent) for King [[Kamehameha II]].{{sfn|Fornander|1880|page=320}} With Kuakini, Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu was the mother of [[Kam\u0101nele]] who was betrothed to [[Kamehameha III]] before her death at a young age.{{sfn|Kamakau|1992|page=391}}{{sfn|Boelen|Broeze|1988|page=100}} Both later remarried. Her final marriage was to Keaweamahi Kinimaka, a chief of lesser rank.{{sfn|Biographical Sketch|1884|pages=72\u201374}}{{sfn|Allen|1995|pages=1\u20136}}\n\n==Conversion to Christianity==\nAmerican Protestant Christian missionaries arrived in Hawaii from New England in 1820. Three years later, around 1823, Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu and her husband Kaiko accepted the new faith along with Queen [[Ke\u014dp\u016bolani]], [[Hoapili]], Princess [[N\u0101hi\u02bbena\u02bbena]], [[Keeaumoku II|Ke\u02bbeaumoku II]], [[Kekau\u02bb\u014dnohi]], [[Wahinepio]] and [[Kaukuna Kahekili]]. These chiefs all attended classes set up by the missionaries on the island of [[Maui]].{{sfn|Stewart|1828|pages=130\u2013131}}\nAfter her conversion to Christianity, she adopted the English name [[Lydia]] Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu.<ref name=\"Court1866\" /> This was the baptismal name of the future queen [[Lili\u02bbuokalani]].{{sfn|Allen|1982|page=40}}\n\n==Adoption of Kal\u0101kaua==\nIn 1836, [[Kapa\u02bbakea]] and [[Keohok\u0101lole]] initially promised their unborn child [[Kal\u0101kaua]] in ''[[h\u0101nai]]'' to [[Kuini Liliha]], a high-ranking chiefess and the widow of High Chief [[Boki (Hawaiian chief)|Boki]] who were both former [[governors of Oahu]]. The Hawaiian custom of h\u0101nai is an informal form of adoption between extended families. However, on the night of his birth at 2:00 a.m. on November 16, 1836, Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu stood outside the grass hut compound on the outskirt of [[Honolulu]] where Keohok\u0101lole was in labor. She took the newborn from his birthplace to her home at Honuakaha, which was one of the residences of King Kamehameha III. Afterward, ''Kuhina Nui'' [[K\u012bna\u02bbu|Elizabeth K\u012bna\u02bbu]], who disliked Liliha, deliberated and ordered his parents to give him to Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu and her husband Kinimaka instead.{{sfn|Biographical Sketch|1884|pages=72\u201374}}{{sfn|Allen|1995|pages=1\u20136}} \n\nHa\u02bbaheo Kaniu brought Kal\u0101kaua with her when the royal court and King Kamehameha III returned to [[Lahaina, Hawaii|L\u0101hain\u0101]], which was the kingdom's capital at the time. At the age of four, Kal\u0101kaua was enrolled with his birth siblings at Honolulu's [[Royal School (Hawaii)|Chiefs' Children's School]] and formally proclaimed by the king as eligible for the throne of the Hawaiian Kingdom.{{sfn|Dibble|1843|page=330}}<ref name=\"Polynesian1844\">{{cite news|title=CALENDAR: Princes and Chiefs eligible to be Rulers|newspaper=The Polynesian|location=Honolulu|date=July 20, 1844|volume=1|issue=9|at=p. 1, col. 3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1844-07-20/ed-1/seq-1|accessdate=October 5, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311050237/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1844-07-20/ed-1/seq-1/|archivedate=March 11, 2017}}; {{harvnb|Cooke|Cooke|1937|pages=v\u2013vi}}; {{harvnb|Van Dyke|2008|page=364}}</ref> \n\nAccording the testimony of Nauhele (a member of her family), Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu died in 1843, in Honolulu. In a verbal will witnessed by Oahu Governor [[Kek\u016ban\u0101o\u02bba]], she bequeathed all her properties in Honolulu and Lahaina and on the islands of [[Hawaii (island)|Hawaii]] and [[Molokai]] to her ''h\u0101nai'' son with her widower Kinimaka holding onto the properties until Kal\u0101kaua came of age.<ref name=\"Court1866\">{{cite book|author=Supreme Court of Hawaii|title=In The Matter Of The Estate Of L. H. Kaniu, Deceased|work=Reports of a Portion of the Decisions Rendered by the Supreme Court of the Hawaiian Islands in Law, Equity, Admiralty, and Probate: 1857\u20131865|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6ckDAAAAYAAJ|year=1866|publisher=Government Press|location=Honolulu|oclc=29559942|pages=82\u201386}}</ref> After her death, Kinimaka was given guardianship over Kal\u0101kaua. Kinimaka would later marry Pai, a subordinate Tahitian chiefess, who treated Kal\u0101kaua as her own until the birth of her own son. Eventually, Kal\u0101kaua returned to live with his birth parents.{{sfn|Allen|1995|pages=1\u20136}} Kinimaka named his daughter Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu Kinimaka after her.{{sfn|McKinzie|1986|pages=99}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Mrs. Lumaheihei Passes Away at Her Home on Young Street|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11778757/mrs_lumaheihei_kaniu_haaheo_uncle/|work=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser |date=January 5, 1901 |page=13}}</ref> Kinimaka died in 1857. In 1858, Kal\u0101kaua successfully sued the heirs of Kinimaka for the rights to Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu's landholding in a case presided by [[Hawaii Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] justice [[George Morison Robertson]].<ref name=\"Court1866\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Allen|first=Helena G.|title=The Betrayal of Liliuokalani: Last Queen of Hawaii, 1838\u20131917|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i2d0AAAAMAAJ|year=1982|publisher=A. H. Clark Company|location=Glendale, CA|isbn=978-0-87062-144-4|oclc=9576325|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Allen|first=Helena G.|title=Kalakaua: Renaissance King|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_SQxAQAAIAAJ|year=1995|publisher=Mutual Publishing|location=Honolulu|isbn=978-1-56647-059-9|oclc=35083815|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Boelen|first1=Jacobus|last2=Broeze|first2=Frank|title=A Merchant's Perspective: Captain Jacobus Boelen's Narrative of His Visit to Hawai\u02bbi in 1828|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qCQxAQAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=Hawaiian Historical Society|location=Honolulu|isbn=978-0-945048-00-8|oclc=18364753|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=|first=|title=Biographical Sketch of His Majesty King Kalakaua|work=Honolulu Almanac and Directory|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100116864|year=1884|location=Honolulu|publisher=P. C. Advertiser Steam Printing Office|pages=72\u201374|oclc=12787107|ref={{harvid|Biographical Sketch|1884}}}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cooke|first1=Amos Starr|authorlink1=Amos Starr Cooke|last2=Cooke|first2=Juliette Montague|editor-last=Richards|editor-first=Mary Atherton|title=The Chiefs' Children School: A Record Compiled from the Diary and Letters of Amos Starr Cooke and Juliette Montague Cooke, by Their Granddaughter Mary Atherton Richards|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001873424|year=1937|publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|oclc=1972890|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dibble|first=Sheldon|authorlink=Sheldon Dibble|title=History of the Sandwich Islands|url=https://archive.org/details/historysandwich00dibbgoog|year=1843|publisher=Press of the Mission Seminary|location=Lahainaluna|oclc=2145112|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fornander|first=Abraham|authorlink=Abraham Fornander|editor-last=Stokes|editor-first=John F. G.|title=An Account of the Polynesian Race: Its Origins and Migrations, and the Ancient History of the Hawaiian People to the Times of Kamehameha I|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tcQNAAAAQAAJ|volume=2|year=1880|publisher=Trubner & Company|location=London|oclc=4823096|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Kamakau|first=Samuel|authorlink=Samuel Kamakau|title=Ruling Chiefs of Hawaii|url=http://www.ulukau.org/elib/cgi-bin/library?c=chiefs&l=en|edition=Revised|year=1992|origyear=1961|publisher=[[Kamehameha Schools]] Press|location=Honolulu|isbn=0-87336-014-1|oclc=25008795|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=McKinzie|first1=Edith Kawelohea|editor-last=Stagner|editor-first=Ishmael W.|title=Hawaiian Genealogies: Extracted from Hawaiian Language Newspapers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QB92bdJ8igwC|volume=2|year=1986|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|location=Honolulu|isbn=978-0-939154-37-1|oclc=12555087|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pratt|first=Elizabeth Kekaaniauokalani Kalaninuiohilaukapu|authorlink=Elizabeth Kekaaniau|title=History of Keoua Kalanikupuapa-i-nui: Father of Hawaii Kings, and His Descendants, with Notes on Kamehameha I, First King of All Hawaii|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofkeouaka00prat|year=1920|publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|oclc=154181545|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stewart|first=Charles Samuel|title=Journal of a Residence in the Sandwich Islands: During the Years 1823, 1824, and 1825|url=https://archive.org/details/journalaresiden00stewgoog|year=1828|publisher=John P. Haven|location=New York|oclc=1179424|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Van Dyke|first1=Jon M.|title=Who Owns the Crown Lands of Hawai`i?|date=2008|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|location=Honolulu, HI|isbn=978-0-8248-3210-0|ref=harv|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/book/8305|via=Project MUSE}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaniu, Haaheo}}\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:1843 deaths]]\n[[Category:Royalty of the Kingdom of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Converts to Christianity from pagan religions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu\n| image = \n| caption =\n| spouse = [[Kaiko\u02bbokalani]]<br />[[Kuakini]]<br />[[Keaweamahi Kinimaka]]\n| issue = [[Kamanele]]\n| father = \n| mother = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| death_date = {{circa|1843}}\n| death_place = [[Honolulu]], [[Oahu]]\n| burial_place = \n}}\n\n'''Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu''' or '''Kaniu\u02bbopioha\u02bbaheo''' (died {{circa|1843}}) was a high chiefess ([[ali\u02bbi]]) and member of the royal family of the [[Hawaiian Kingdom]]. She was also known as '''Lydia Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu'''.\n\n==Genealogy and family==\nHa\u02bbaheo Kaniu was born in the late 18th-century. Sources on Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu's genealogy are conflicting. An 1858 court case named Kalailua as the mother of Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu and stated Kalailua was sister of [[\u02bbAikanaka (father of Keohok\u0101lole)|\u02bbAikanaka]] (maternal grandfather of her future ''h\u0101nai'' son [[Kal\u0101kaua]]).<ref name=\"Court1866\" /> An 1874 account in the [[Hawaiian language]] newspaper ''Ka Nuhou Hawaii'' listed her parent as Kalailua and Keaweaimoku and further specified that Kalailua was the child of Kaoo and Kamakaeheikuli.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ka Papa Alii O Hawaii I Hoonohonoho Pono Ia|date=January 7, 1874|newspaper=Ka Nuhou Hawaii|volume=1|issue=10|page=3|url=http://nupepa.org/gsdl2.5/cgi-bin/nupepa?e=d-0nupepa--00-0-0--010---4-----mid---0-1l--1en-Zz-1---20-about---0003-1-0000utfZz-8-00&a=d&cl=CL2.30&d=HASH04cfa1db90bd9eb14e1b7d.3|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHistorian [[Abraham Fornander]] named High Chiefess \u02bbAkahi as her mother, who was a sister of [[Keawemauhili]], Ali\u02bbi Nui of [[Hilo, Hawaii|Hilo]] and a rival of King [[Kamehameha I]] who conquered the Hawaiian Islands into a unified kingdom by 1810. This \u02bbAkahi was the foster mother of Keawemauhili's orphan daughter [[Kapi\u02bbolani (chiefess)|Kapi\u02bbolani]] who became a later famous convert to [[Christianity]].{{sfn|Fornander|1880|page=320}} According to historian Sammy Amalu, she was the daughter of \u02bbAkahi-a-Kawalu (different from Fornander's \u02bbAkahi) and [[Ke\u014dua|Ke\u014dua Kalanikupuapa\u02bb\u012bkalaninui Ahilapalapa]], the father of Kamehameha I.{{sfn|Pratt|1920|pages=40\u201342}}<ref name=\"Keoua\">{{Hawaiian Dictionaries|Sacred Prince Keoua Had Six Official Wives|dic=royal|id=D0.4.99|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> \n\nHa\u02bbaheo Kaniu married to [[Kaiko\u02bbokalani]], the son of Kamehameha I and [[Peleuli]].{{sfn|Fornander|1880|page=320}}{{sfn|Kamakau|1992|page=250}} She also married [[Kuakini]], who adopted the name John Adams and served as [[Governors of Hawaii (island)|Governor of Hawaii Island]]. Kuakini was also the younger brother of Kamehameha I's favorite wife [[Ka\u02bbahumanu]] who served as ''[[Kuhina Nui]]'' (regent) for King [[Kamehameha II]].{{sfn|Fornander|1880|page=320}} With Kuakini, Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu was the mother of [[Kam\u0101nele]] who was betrothed to [[Kamehameha III]] before her death at a young age.{{sfn|Kamakau|1992|page=391}}{{sfn|Boelen|Broeze|1988|page=100}} Both later remarried. Her final marriage was to Keaweamahi Kinimaka, a chief of lesser rank.{{sfn|Biographical Sketch|1884|pages=72\u201374}}{{sfn|Allen|1995|pages=1\u20136}}\n\n==Conversion to Christianity==\nAmerican Protestant Christian missionaries arrived in Hawaii from New England in 1820. Three years later, around 1823, Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu and her husband Kaiko accepted the new faith along with Queen [[Ke\u014dp\u016bolani]], [[Hoapili]], Princess [[N\u0101hi\u02bbena\u02bbena]], [[Keeaumoku II|Ke\u02bbeaumoku II]], [[Kekau\u02bb\u014dnohi]], [[Wahinepio]] and [[Kaukuna Kahekili]]. These chiefs all attended classes set up by the missionaries on the island of [[Maui]].{{sfn|Stewart|1828|pages=130\u2013131}}\nAfter her conversion to Christianity, she adopted the English name [[Lydia]] Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu.<ref name=\"Court1866\" /> This was the baptismal name of the future queen [[Lili\u02bbuokalani]].{{sfn|Allen|1982|page=40}}\n\n==Adoption of Kal\u0101kaua==\nIn 1836, [[Kapa\u02bbakea]] and [[Keohok\u0101lole]] initially promised their unborn child [[Kal\u0101kaua]] in ''[[h\u0101nai]]'' to [[Kuini Liliha]], a high-ranking chiefess and the widow of High Chief [[Boki (Hawaiian chief)|Boki]] who were both former [[governors of Oahu]]. The Hawaiian custom of h\u0101nai is an informal form of adoption between extended families. However, on the night of his birth at 2:00 a.m. on November 16, 1836, Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu stood outside the grass hut compound on the outskirt of [[Honolulu]] where Keohok\u0101lole was in labor. She took the newborn from his birthplace to her home at Honuakaha, which was one of the residence of King Kamehameha III. Afterward, ''Kuhina Nui'' [[K\u012bna\u02bbu|Elizabeth K\u012bna\u02bbu]], who disliked Liliha, deliberated and ordered his parents to give him to Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu and her husband Kinimaka instead.{{sfn|Biographical Sketch|1884|pages=72\u201374}}{{sfn|Allen|1995|pages=1\u20136}} \n\nHa\u02bbaheo Kaniu brought Kal\u0101kaua with her when the royal court and King Kamehameha III returned to [[Lahaina, Hawaii|L\u0101hain\u0101]], which was the kingdom's capital at the time. At the age of four, Kal\u0101kaua was enrolled with his birth siblings at Honolulu's [[Royal School (Hawaii)|Chiefs' Children's School]] and formally proclaimed by the king as eligible for the throne of the Hawaiian Kingdom.{{sfn|Dibble|1843|page=330}}<ref name=\"Polynesian1844\">{{cite news|title=CALENDAR: Princes and Chiefs eligible to be Rulers|newspaper=The Polynesian|location=Honolulu|date=July 20, 1844|volume=1|issue=9|at=p. 1, col. 3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1844-07-20/ed-1/seq-1|accessdate=October 5, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170311050237/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015408/1844-07-20/ed-1/seq-1/|archivedate=March 11, 2017}}; {{harvnb|Cooke|Cooke|1937|pages=v\u2013vi}}; {{harvnb|Van Dyke|2008|page=364}}</ref> \n\nAccording the testimony of Nauhele (a member of her family), Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu died in 1843, in Honolulu. In a verbal will witnessed by Oahu Governor [[Kek\u016ban\u0101o\u02bba]], she bequeathed all her properties in Honolulu and Lahaina and on the islands of [[Hawaii (island)|Hawaii]] and [[Molokai]] to her ''h\u0101nai'' son with her widower Kinimaka holding onto the properties until Kal\u0101kaua came of age.<ref name=\"Court1866\">{{cite book|author=Supreme Court of Hawaii|title=In The Matter Of The Estate Of L. H. Kaniu, Deceased|work=Reports of a Portion of the Decisions Rendered by the Supreme Court of the Hawaiian Islands in Law, Equity, Admiralty, and Probate: 1857\u20131865|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6ckDAAAAYAAJ|year=1866|publisher=Government Press|location=Honolulu|oclc=29559942|pages=82\u201386}}</ref> After her death, Kinimaka was given guardianship over Kal\u0101kaua. Kinimaka would later marry Pai, a subordinate Tahitian chiefess, who treated Kal\u0101kaua as her own until the birth of her own son. Eventually, Kal\u0101kaua returned to live with his birth parents.{{sfn|Allen|1995|pages=1\u20136}} Kinimaka named his daughter Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu Kinimaka after her.{{sfn|McKinzie|1986|pages=99}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Mrs. Lumaheihei Passes Away at Her Home on Young Street|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11778757/mrs_lumaheihei_kaniu_haaheo_uncle/|work=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser |date=January 5, 1901 |page=13}}</ref> Kinimaka died in 1857. In 1858, Kal\u0101kaua successfully sued the heirs of Kinimaka for the rights to Ha\u02bbaheo Kaniu's landholding in a case presided by [[Hawaii Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] justice [[George Morison Robertson]].<ref name=\"Court1866\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Allen|first=Helena G.|title=The Betrayal of Liliuokalani: Last Queen of Hawaii, 1838\u20131917|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i2d0AAAAMAAJ|year=1982|publisher=A. H. Clark Company|location=Glendale, CA|isbn=978-0-87062-144-4|oclc=9576325|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Allen|first=Helena G.|title=Kalakaua: Renaissance King|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_SQxAQAAIAAJ|year=1995|publisher=Mutual Publishing|location=Honolulu|isbn=978-1-56647-059-9|oclc=35083815|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Boelen|first1=Jacobus|last2=Broeze|first2=Frank|title=A Merchant's Perspective: Captain Jacobus Boelen's Narrative of His Visit to Hawai\u02bbi in 1828|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qCQxAQAAIAAJ|year=1988|publisher=Hawaiian Historical Society|location=Honolulu|isbn=978-0-945048-00-8|oclc=18364753|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=|first=|title=Biographical Sketch of His Majesty King Kalakaua|work=Honolulu Almanac and Directory|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/100116864|year=1884|location=Honolulu|publisher=P. C. Advertiser Steam Printing Office|pages=72\u201374|oclc=12787107|ref={{harvid|Biographical Sketch|1884}}}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cooke|first1=Amos Starr|authorlink1=Amos Starr Cooke|last2=Cooke|first2=Juliette Montague|editor-last=Richards|editor-first=Mary Atherton|title=The Chiefs' Children School: A Record Compiled from the Diary and Letters of Amos Starr Cooke and Juliette Montague Cooke, by Their Granddaughter Mary Atherton Richards|url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001873424|year=1937|publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|oclc=1972890|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dibble|first=Sheldon|authorlink=Sheldon Dibble|title=History of the Sandwich Islands|url=https://archive.org/details/historysandwich00dibbgoog|year=1843|publisher=Press of the Mission Seminary|location=Lahainaluna|oclc=2145112|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Fornander|first=Abraham|authorlink=Abraham Fornander|editor-last=Stokes|editor-first=John F. G.|title=An Account of the Polynesian Race: Its Origins and Migrations, and the Ancient History of the Hawaiian People to the Times of Kamehameha I|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tcQNAAAAQAAJ|volume=2|year=1880|publisher=Trubner & Company|location=London|oclc=4823096|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Kamakau|first=Samuel|authorlink=Samuel Kamakau|title=Ruling Chiefs of Hawaii|url=http://www.ulukau.org/elib/cgi-bin/library?c=chiefs&l=en|edition=Revised|year=1992|origyear=1961|publisher=[[Kamehameha Schools]] Press|location=Honolulu|isbn=0-87336-014-1|oclc=25008795|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=McKinzie|first1=Edith Kawelohea|editor-last=Stagner|editor-first=Ishmael W.|title=Hawaiian Genealogies: Extracted from Hawaiian Language Newspapers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QB92bdJ8igwC|volume=2|year=1986|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|location=Honolulu|isbn=978-0-939154-37-1|oclc=12555087|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pratt|first=Elizabeth Kekaaniauokalani Kalaninuiohilaukapu|authorlink=Elizabeth Kekaaniau|title=History of Keoua Kalanikupuapa-i-nui: Father of Hawaii Kings, and His Descendants, with Notes on Kamehameha I, First King of All Hawaii|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofkeouaka00prat|year=1920|publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|location=Honolulu|oclc=154181545|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stewart|first=Charles Samuel|title=Journal of a Residence in the Sandwich Islands: During the Years 1823, 1824, and 1825|url=https://archive.org/details/journalaresiden00stewgoog|year=1828|publisher=John P. Haven|location=New York|oclc=1179424|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Van Dyke|first1=Jon M.|title=Who Owns the Crown Lands of Hawai`i?|date=2008|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|location=Honolulu, HI|isbn=978-0-8248-3210-0|ref=harv|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/book/8305|via=Project MUSE}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaniu, Haaheo}}\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:1843 deaths]]\n[[Category:Royalty of the Kingdom of Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Converts to Christianity from pagan religions]]\n", "name_user": "Maile66", "label