18.pdf |website=govinfo.gov |date=September 9, 1983}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Soviet Union}}\n| 1984\n| 4\n| Death of Soviet leader [[Yuri Andropov]]\n| <ref>{{cite web |last1=Reed |first1=Steven R. |title=Andropov's death leaves Soviet Union leaderless |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/02/10/Andropovs-death-leaves-Soviet-Union-leaderless/5909445237200/ |website=UPI |date=February 10, 1984}}</ref><ref name=Russia/>\n|-\n| {{flag|Guinea}}\n| 1984\n| 40\n| Death of President [[Ahmed S\u00e9kou Tour\u00e9]]\n| <ref>{{cite web |last1=May |first1=Clifford D. |title=Guinea's President, Sekou Toure, Dies in Cleveland Clinic |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/03/28/obituaries/guinea-s-president-sekou-toure-dies-in-cleveland-clinic.html |website=The New York Times |date=March 28, 1984}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|India}}\n| rowspan=2| 1984\n| 13\n| rowspan=2| [[Assassination of Indira Gandhi|Assassination]] of Prime Minister [[Indira Gandhi]]\n| <ref>{{cite web |last1=Crossette |first1=Barbara |title=India Hangs Two Sikhs Convicted In Assassination of Indira Gandhi |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/01/06/world/india-hangs-two-sikhs-convicted-in-assassination-of-indira-gandhi.html |website=The New York Times |date=January 6, 1989}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Bulgaria}}\n| 1\n| <ref>\u0423\u043a\u0430\u0437 \u2116 3904 \u043e\u0442 1 \u043d\u043e\u0435\u043c\u0432\u0440\u0438 1984 \u0433. \u041e\u0431\u043d. \u0414\u0412. \u0431\u0440. 88 \u043e\u0442 6 \u043d\u043e\u0435\u043c\u0432\u0440\u0438 1984 \u0433.</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Soviet Union}}\n| rowspan=2| 1985\n| 3\n| rowspan=2| Death of Soviet leader [[Konstantin Chernenko]]\n| <ref>{{cite web |last1=Doder |first1=Dusko |title=Gorbachev Becomes Soviet Leader Hours After Chernenko Dies at 73 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1985/03/12/gorbachev-becomes-soviet-leader-hours-after-chernenko-dies-at-73/696b5b18-96ae-4428-bbff-33aa5e3e707b/ |website=The Washington Post |date=March 12, 1985}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|East Germany}